tional Studies -- tPart Three: Representation and Its Discontents -- tArtist Statement -- t10. Meet Me in Toronto: The Re-exhibition of Artifacts from the 1904 Louisiana Purchase Exposition at the Royal Ontario Museum -- t11. From the Pearl of the Orient to Uptown: A Collaborative Arts-Based Inquiry with Filipino Youth Activists in Montreal -- t12. Borrowing Privileges: Tagalog, Filipinos, and the Toronto Public Library -- t13. Abject Beings: Filipina/os in Canadian Historical Narrations -- t14. Between the Sheets -- tPart Four: Youth Spaces and Subjectivities -- tArtist Statement -- t15. Scales of Violence from the Body to the Globe: Slain Filipino Youth in Canadian Cities -- t16. Kapisanan: Resignifying Diasporic Post/colonial Art and Artists -- t17. Educated Minorities: The Experiences of Filipino Canadian University Students -- t18. Mas Maputi Ako sa ’yo (I’m lighter than you): The Spatial Politics of Intraracial Colourism among Filipina/o Youth in the Greater Toronto Area -- t19. The Social Construction of ‘Filipina/o Studies’: Youth Spaces and Subjectivities -- tPart Five: Afterword -- t20. Contemplating New Spaces in Canadian Studies -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Philippines became Canada’s largest source of short- and long-term migrants in 2010, surpassing China and India, both of which are more than ten times larger. The fourth-largest racialized minority group in the country, the Filipino community is frequently understood by such figures as the victimized nanny, the selfless nurse, and the gangster youth. On one hand, these narratives concentrate attention, in narrow and stereotypical ways, on critical issues. On the other, they render other problems facing Filipino communities invisible.This landmark book, the first wide-ranging edited collection on Filipinos in Canada, explores gender, migration and labour, youth spaces and subjectivities, representation and community resistance to certain representations. Looking at these from the vantage points of anthropology, cultural studies, education, geography, history, information science, literature, political science, sociology, and women and gender studies, Filipinos in Canada provides a strong foundation for future work in this area.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aFilipinoszCanadaxEconomic conditions. 0aFilipinoszCanadaxHistory. 0aFilipinoszCanadaxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Asian American Studies.2bisacsh1 aAguinaldo, Jeffrey P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAngeles, Leonora C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAstorga-Garcia, Mila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBalmes, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCatungal, John Paul C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCatungal, John Paul c., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColoma, Roland Sintos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorrea, Celia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaga, Jean Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDamasco, Valerie G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavidson, Lisa M. , eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aDavidson, Lisa M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Leon, Conely, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEric, Josephine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEsguerra, Enrico F., econtributor.4ctb4h